<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06087315 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06087315 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  CAMPBELL; CITY; BRIEF  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  How fast is too fast? And how slow is too slow?;    When it comes to traffic,proper speed limits are established by state vehicle code or, for certainstreets, by city councils.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Extra 3  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  CITY REVIEWS TRAFFIC SPEED LIMITS  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Campbell News  </MEMO><TEXT>     The Campbell City Council last week introduced an amendment to its 1978Speed Limit Ordinance establishing comprehensive speed limits for arterial,collector and a limited number of through streets in the city. Mostresidential and business district have a speed limit of 25 miles per hour,which is set by state vehicle code.;    Most of the present speed limits onthe city's streets were retained.;    City traffic engineers made new surveysat 141 locations over the past three months. Establishing limits based ontraffic engineering analysis is required if the city is to use radarenforcement on its streets.;     MOVE TO WIDEN PAGE STREET; The preparing ofan appraisal and a purchase offer for a 1-foot-wide by 339-foot-long piece ofproperty on Page Street in Campbell was authorized by the city council lastweek.;    The property is needed to complete the widening of Page Street to 60feet, a condition of approval for a 32-unit townhouse project approved by thecouncil last January. The developer has been unsuccessful in his attempts topurchase the property and, without it, cannot proceed with securing buildingpermits.;    The city has been asked to condemn the property since it willbecome part of the public right-of-way. Should the city's offer to purchasethe property be rejected, the council would then have to decide whether toacquire through eminent domain.;    Tracer of stolen vehicles; Officer SteveNorris' ability to recover stolen vehicles has won him his second CaliforniaHighway Patrol/California State Automobile Association &quot;10851 Award.&quot;;    Toqualify for the award, Norris made arrests that resulted in the recovery ofsix stolen vehicles in three months, and also recovered several other stolenvehicles, according to Campbell Police Sgt. Ed Fallgatter.;    Norris, afour-year veteran on the force, also won the &quot;10851 Award&quot; in October 1990.California Vehicle Section 10851 refers to stolen vehicles.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Mercury News Staff Writer Michael Cronk compiled this report.  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910327  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Wednesday  </DAY><MONTH>  March  </MONTH><PG.COL>  3  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  349  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Wednesday March 27, 199100087315,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>